    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Halliburton Deal</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jonathan D Kaufelt letter, commenting on August 17 article, says Halliburton Co went too far by giving Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney stock options that would vest during Cheney's possible tenure in office</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Retirement Deal, Cheney Could Keep Options in Office'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>There is a ready measure of what is appropriate in the exit package that the Halliburton Company is giving Dick Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president: What would he receive upon termination by reason of death or disability?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Retirement Deal, Cheney Could Keep Options in Office'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>There is a ready measure of what is appropriate in the exit package that the Halliburton Company is giving Dick Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president: What would he receive upon termination by reason of death or disability?</p>
        <p>The ''death or disability'' standard pinpoints what the parties think is fair when an executive cannot render any further services and the company cannot expect any further benefit. If Mr. Cheney is getting more than he would receive in a death-or-disability termination, something is awry.</p>
        <p>It is unusual, in my experience, to see such lengthy extensions of both vesting and exercise periods for stock options in a voluntary termination. I think the Halliburton board went too far.</p>
        <p>JONATHAN D. KAUFELT  Los Angeles, Aug. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
